% @
% \caption{Distribution of ministerial duration across Peru's political frameworks for appointments to the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF) and the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM). Boxes represent the interquartile range, horizontal lines indicate the median, whiskers extend to 1.5 times the interquartile range, and points denote observations beyond the whiskers. Sample sizes are reported above each box.}
% \label{fig:epoch_descriptives}
% 
% 
% Figure~\ref{fig:epoch_descriptives} provides an initial description of ministerial duration across Peru's political frameworks using appointments to the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF) and the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM). Substantial historical variation is immediately apparent. Median ministerial duration varies considerably across political frameworks, from 119 days during the State Formation framework to 314 days during the Transition and Crisis framework, with the remaining frameworks occupying intermediate positions. The interquartile ranges also differ substantially across historical periods. The Power-Sharing State and the Transition and Crisis frameworks exhibit both the highest median durations and the greatest dispersion, whereas the Current Critical Juncture displays comparatively short ministerial spells concentrated within a narrower range.
% 
% The distributions are consistently right-skewed, with a relatively small number of exceptionally long ministerial appointments extending well beyond the upper quartile in every framework. These descriptive patterns suggest that observed ministerial continuity has not remained constant throughout Peru's republican history. However, boxplots summarize only the observed distribution of ministerial durations. They neither account for right-censored observations nor evaluate whether the differences between political frameworks are statistically distinguishable. Those questions are addressed through the survival analyses that follow.
% 
% These descriptive patterns suggest that observed ministerial continuity has not remained constant throughout Peru's republican history. However, boxplots summarize only the observed distribution of ministerial durations. They neither account for right-censored observations nor evaluate whether the differences between political frameworks are statistically distinguishable. Those questions require event-history methods and are examined in the analyses that follow.
% 
% %% Kaplan--Meier survival curves here.
% 
% \begin{figure}
% \centering
% <<fig:km_epochs,echo=FALSE,fig=TRUE>>=
% library(survival)
% library(survminer)
% library(dplyr)
% library(ggplot2)
% 
% datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
%   filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF"))
% 
% km_epoch <- survfit(
%   Surv(duration, event) ~ political_framework,
%   data = datos_pcm_mef
% )
% 
% s <- surv_summary(km_epoch) |>
%   mutate(
%     epoch = gsub("^political_framework=", "", strata)
%   )
% 
% meds <- s |>
%   group_by(epoch) |>
%   slice_min(order_by = abs(surv - 0.5), n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) |>
%   ungroup()
% 
% ann_df <- meds |>
%   mutate(
%     num = as.numeric(gsub("^([0-9]+).*", "\\1", political_framework)),
%     ord = match(num, c(1, 2, 6, 5, 3, 4))
%   ) |>
%   arrange(ord) |>
%   mutate(
%     x_text = c(230, 360, 500, 640, 780, 920),
%     y_text = c(.545, .550, .555, .560, .565, .570),
%     label = as.character(num)
%   )
% 
% ggplot(
%   s,
%   aes(
%     x = time,
%     y = surv,
%     colour = as.ordered(political_framework),
%     linetype = political_framework
%   )
% ) +
%   geom_step(linewidth = 1.5) +
%   geom_hline(
%     yintercept = 0.5,
%     linetype = "dashed",
%     colour = "grey50",
%     alpha = 0.6
%   ) +
%   geom_point(
%     data = ann_df,
%     aes(x = time, y = 0.5),
%     inherit.aes = FALSE,
%     colour = "grey30",
%     size = 0
%   ) +
%   geom_segment(
%     data = ann_df,
%     aes(x = x_text, y = y_text, xend = time, yend = 0.5),
%     inherit.aes = FALSE,
%     colour = "grey40",
%     linewidth = 0.35
%   ) +
%   geom_label(
%   data = ann_df,
%   aes(x = x_text, y = y_text, label = label),
%   inherit.aes = FALSE,
%   hjust = 0.5,
%   vjust = 0.5,
%   size = 3.5,
%   colour = "grey20",
%   fill = "white",
%   label.size = 0.25,
%   fontface = "bold"
% )+
%   labs(
%     x = "Ministerial duration in days",
%     y = "Survival probability",
%     colour = NULL,
%     linetype = NULL
%   ) +
%   scale_color_brewer(type = "div", palette = "Spectral") +
%   theme_classic2() +
%   theme(
%     legend.position = c(.75, .75),
%     legend.background = element_rect(
%       fill = "white",
%       colour = "grey60"
%     ),
%     legend.key = element_blank()
%   ) + annotate(
%   "text",
%   x = 1750,
%   y = .51,
%   label = "Median survival (S = 0.5)",
%   hjust = 1,
%   size = 3,
%   colour = "grey20"
% )
% @
% \caption{Kaplan–Meier estimates of ministerial continuity across political frameworks. Curves represent the estimated probability that a minister remains in office beyond a given duration. Numbers identify the six political frameworks listed in Table~\ref{tab:frameworks}. Analyses are restricted to appointments to the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM) and the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF).}
% \label{fig:km_epochs}
% \end{figure}
% 
% 
% 
% Figure~\ref{fig:km_epochs} extends the descriptive evidence by accounting for censoring and estimating the probability that ministers remain in office over time. The survival curves reveal substantial heterogeneity across political frameworks, indicating that organizational continuity differed systematically throughout Peru's republican history. Importantly, the curves do not exhibit a monotonic historical progression. Frameworks associated with later historical periods do not uniformly display greater ministerial continuity than earlier ones. Instead, each political framework appears to be associated with a distinct pattern of organizational continuity, with some historical environments characterized by relatively rapid ministerial turnover and others by more sustained tenure. This visual evidence is consistent with Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_continuity}, which predicts that political frameworks shape organizational continuity without assuming that successive political frameworks necessarily represent cumulative institutional improvement. Formal statistical comparisons of these survival functions are presented next.
% 
% 
% 
% %% Log-rank comparison table here.
% 
% <<tab:logrank_epoch, echo=FALSE, results=tex, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
% library(dplyr)
% library(survival)
% library(knitr)
% library(kableExtra)
% 
% datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
%   filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF"))
% 
% logrank_epoch <- survdiff(
%   Surv(duration, event) ~ political_framework,
%   data = datos_pcm_mef
% )
% 
% chisq_epoch <- logrank_epoch$chisq
% df_epoch <- length(logrank_epoch$n) - 1
% p_epoch <- pchisq(chisq_epoch, df = df_epoch, lower.tail = FALSE)
% 
% logrank_summary <- tibble(
%   Test = "Global log-rank test",
%   `Chi-square` = round(chisq_epoch, 2),
%   df = df_epoch,
%   `p-value` = ifelse(p_epoch < .001, "< .001", round(p_epoch, 3))
% )
% 
% logrank_summary |>
%   kable(
%     format = "latex",
%     booktabs = TRUE,
%     escape = FALSE,
%     align = c("l", "r", "r", "r"),
%     linesep = "",
%     caption = paste0(
%       "Global Log-Rank Test Across Political Frameworks",
%       "\\label{tab:logrank_epoch}"
%     )
%   ) |>
%   footnote(
%     general = paste(
%       "\\footnotesize The test evaluates the null hypothesis that ministerial survival functions",
%       "are identical across political frameworks. Results are based on PCM and MEF appointments."
%     ),
%     threeparttable = TRUE,
%     escape = FALSE,
%     general_title = "\\mbox{}\\vskip 1mm \\footnotesize\\textit{Note: }"
%   )
% @
% 
% 
% The visual differences observed in Figure~\ref{fig:km_epochs} are confirmed by the global log-rank test reported in Table~\ref{tab:logrank_epoch}. The null hypothesis that all political frameworks share the same survival function is decisively rejected ($\chi^{2}=46.47$, $df=5$, $p<.001$), indicating that the observed variation in ministerial continuity is unlikely to be attributable to random sampling variation alone. Taken together, the descriptive statistics, Kaplan--Meier estimates, and log-rank test provide consistent evidence that historically distinct political frameworks generated significantly different patterns of ministerial continuity. The remaining question is whether these differences persist after simultaneously comparing all political frameworks within a multivariate event-history model. That question is addressed through the Cox proportional hazards model presented next.
% 
% 
% %% Cox proportional hazards model here.
% 
% 
% <<tab:cox_epoch, echo=FALSE, results=tex, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
% library(dplyr)
% library(survival)
% library(knitr)
% 
% datos_pcm_mef <- gatopardo |>
%   filter(portfolio %in% c("PCM", "MEF")) |>
%   mutate(
%     epoch_model = factor(
%       as.character(political_framework),
%       levels = c(
%         "5. Democracy without Parties",
%         "1. State Formation",
%         "2. Oligarchic State",
%         "3. Power-Sharing State",
%         "4. Transition and Crisis",
%         "6. Current Critical Juncture"
%       )
%     )
%   )
% 
% cox_epoch <- coxph(
%   Surv(duration, event) ~ epoch_model,
%   data = datos_pcm_mef
% )
% 
% cox_table <- summary(cox_epoch)
% 
% cox_results <- data.frame(
%   Epoch = rownames(cox_table$coefficients),
%   Hazard_Ratio = cox_table$coefficients[, "exp(coef)"],
%   CI_Lower = cox_table$conf.int[, "lower .95"],
%   CI_Upper = cox_table$conf.int[, "upper .95"],
%   p_value = cox_table$coefficients[, "Pr(>|z|)"]
% ) |>
%   mutate(
%     Epoch = gsub("^epoch_model", "", Epoch),
%     Hazard_Ratio = round(Hazard_Ratio, 2),
%     CI = paste0(round(CI_Lower, 2), "--", round(CI_Upper, 2)),
%     p_value = ifelse(p_value < .001, "< .001", round(p_value, 3))
%   ) |>
%   select(
%     `Political Framework` = Epoch,
%     Hazard_Ratio,
%     CI,
%     p_value
%   )
% 
% cox_results |>
%   kable(
%     caption = paste0(
%       "Cox Proportional Hazards Model of Ministerial Replacement by Political Framework",
%       "\\label{tab:cox_epoch}"
%     ),
%     booktabs = TRUE,
%     format = "latex",
%     escape = FALSE,
%     row.names = FALSE,
%     col.names = c(
%       "Political Framework",
%       "Relative Hazard",
%       "95\\% CI",
%       "p-value"
%     ),
%     linesep = ""
%   )|>
%   footnote(
%     general = paste(
%       "\\\\footnotesize The reference category is Democracy without Parties. Hazard ratios above one indicate a higher risk of ministerial replacement relative to the reference framework, whereas hazard ratios below one indicate a lower risk of ministerial replacement.",
%       "Results are based on PCM and MEF appointments"),
%     threeparttable = TRUE,
%     escape = FALSE,
%     # Shortened the gap to 1.5mm and shrunk text to scriptsize
%     general_title = "\\\\mbox{}\\\\vskip 1mm \\\\footnotesize\\\\textit{Note: }"
%   )
% @
% 
% The Cox model reported in Table~\ref{tab:cox_epoch} quantifies the magnitude of these historical differences by estimating the relative hazard of ministerial replacement while treating the Democracy without Parties framework as the reference category. The model reinforces the historical patterns suggested by the descriptive statistics, Kaplan–Meier estimates, and global log-rank test. Ministers serving during the State Formation period faced a 71\% higher hazard of replacement than those serving during the post-1993 framework, while the Oligarchic State also exhibited significantly greater ministerial turnover. The Current Critical Juncture presents the highest estimated hazard of replacement, more than doubling the risk observed under the reference framework. In contrast, the Power-Sharing State and the Transition and Crisis frameworks do not differ significantly from the Democracy without Parties period.
% 
% Taken together, the results indicate that organizational continuity has varied substantially across Peru's political frameworks. At the same time, the historical pattern is clearly non-monotonic. The post-1993 political framework does not represent the culmination of a steady historical progression toward increasingly stable ministerial organizations, nor do earlier frameworks uniformly exhibit lower continuity. Instead, continuity appears to depend on the particular institutional environment created by each political framework.
% 
% This interpretation is particularly important from a comparative-historical perspective. Critical junctures are often associated with major institutional change, but the present results suggest that institutional change alone should not be equated with improved organizational continuity. Different critical junctures produced different organizational environments, some more conducive to continuity than others.
% 
% This finding is broadly consistent with Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_continuity}. The proposition does not predict progressive institutional improvement, but rather that different political frameworks generate different organizational conditions under which continuity may be preserved or disrupted. From the perspective of Axiom~\ref{ax:continuity}, these historical differences imply that successive political frameworks created different opportunities for organizational knowledge accumulation. The analyses do not establish that organizations accumulated more knowledge under one framework than another; they indicate only that the organizational conditions necessary for such accumulation varied historically.
% 
% Historical variation alone, however, does not establish whether all governmental organizations experienced similar continuity conditions within the same political framework. Proposition~\ref{prop:framework_pb} suggests that political systems may selectively preserve particular organizations according to their strategic importance. The following subsection therefore shifts the focus from historical variation to organizational variation by comparing ministerial continuity across governmental organizations.
% 
% 
% %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% \subsection{Protective Belts Across Governmental Organizations}
% %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% 
% The second empirical question follows directly from Propositions~\ref{prop:framework_pb} and~\ref{prop:protective_belt}. The previous subsection established that organizational continuity varied across Peru's successive political frameworks. Historical variation alone, however, cannot determine whether all governmental organizations operating within the same political framework experienced comparable continuity conditions. If political frameworks generate differentiated configurations of protective belts, organizational continuity should also vary across governmental organizations exposed to the same historical environment.
% 
% The analyses therefore shift from historical variation to organizational variation. Ministerial appointments are used as observable indicators of continuity within governmental organizations, allowing comparisons across portfolios while holding constant the broader institutional context in which those organizations operate.
% 
% Particular attention is given to the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF) and the Presidency of the Council of Ministers (PCM). As argued in the Peru case, these organizations occupy contrasting institutional positions within the executive. The MEF concentrates organizational capabilities associated with macroeconomic governance and international policy credibility, whereas the PCM coordinates cabinet politics and absorbs much of the executive's day-to-day political pressure. The remaining ministries—Interior, Education, and Health—are incorporated as organizational benchmarks representing security and public service provision.
% 
% The objective is not to determine which ministry performs better, nor to attribute organizational performance to ministerial tenure. Rather, the analyses evaluate whether organizational continuity varies systematically across governmental organizations in ways consistent with the theoretical concept of protective belts.
% 
% %% Descriptive comparison across portfolios here.
% 
% Before comparing survival functions, it is useful to examine the observed distribution of ministerial duration across governmental organizations. As in the previous subsection, these descriptive statistics do not account for censoring and therefore should not be interpreted as estimates of organizational continuity. Rather, they provide an initial characterization of the observed ministerial spells prior to formal survival analysis.
% 
% <<tab:portfolio_descriptives_all, results=tex, echo=FALSE>>=
% library(dplyr)
% library(knitr)
% 
% gatopardo |>
%   group_by(portfolio) |>
%   summarise(
%     N = n(),
%     Q1 = quantile(duration, .25, na.rm = TRUE),
%     Median = median(duration, na.rm = TRUE),
%     Q3 = quantile(duration, .75, na.rm = TRUE),
%     Max = max(duration, na.rm = TRUE),
%     .groups = "drop"
%   ) |>
%   arrange(desc(Median)) |>
%   kable(
%     caption = "Ministerial Duration Across Governmental Organizations
%     \\label{tab:portfolio_descriptives_all}",
%     booktabs = TRUE,
%     format = "latex",
%     digits = 0,
%     linesep = ""
%   )
% @
% 
% Table~\ref{tab:portfolio_descriptives_all} suggests substantial variation in ministerial duration across governmental organizations. The Ministry of Health exhibits the longest observed median duration (318 days), followed by Education (234 days), whereas the Ministry of Economy and Finance presents the shortest median duration (151 days). At first glance, these descriptive statistics appear inconsistent with the theoretical expectation that organizations responsible for strategically valuable forms of organizational knowledge should experience greater continuity.
% 
% This apparent contradiction, however, should be interpreted with caution. Descriptive summaries ignore the timing of ministerial exits, treat all observed spells as complete, and do not account for the small number of right-censored observations. Moreover, they compare organizations across the entire republican period without considering the historical environments in which those appointments occurred. Consequently, these descriptive patterns should be regarded as preliminary rather than conclusive. The survival analyses that follow evaluate whether the observed differences persist once censoring and the temporal structure of ministerial replacement are explicitly incorporated.
% 
% %% Kaplan--Meier comparison across portfolios here.
% 
% \begin{figure}[!htbp]
% \centering
% <<fig:km_portfolios_all, echo=FALSE, fig=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
