%       "\\footnotesize The reference category is PCM.",
%       "Hazard ratios below one indicate a lower risk of ministerial replacement relative to PCM.",
%       "Hazard ratios above one indicate a higher risk of ministerial replacement."
%     ),
%     threeparttable = TRUE,
%     escape = FALSE,
%     general_title = "\\mbox{}\\vskip 1mm \\footnotesize\\textit{Note: }"
%   )
% @
% 
% %% Explanation and interpretation here.
% 
% 
% 
% %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% \subsection{Globalization and the Emergence of a Protective Belt}
% %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% 
% The historical interpretation developed in the previous section suggests that the organizational reconstruction initiated during the 1990s may have altered the distribution of organizational continuity within the Peruvian state. If the post-1993 political framework selectively strengthened macroeconomic governance, the Ministry of Economy and Finance should begin to exhibit continuity patterns that differ from organizations primarily exposed to political coordination.
% 
% This subsection explores that possibility through alternative historical specifications. The analyses compare organizational continuity before and after Peru's consolidation within the contemporary global economy and examine whether portfolio differences became more pronounced following the post-1990 institutional settlement.
% 
% %% Alternative historical specification table here.
% 
% %% Survival curves before and after 2001 here.
% 
% %% Cox interaction models here.
% 
% %% Robustness comparison here.
% 
% %% Explanation and interpretation here.
% 
% 
% 
% %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% \subsection{Accounting for Presidential Heterogeneity}
% %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% 
% Ministerial continuity may also depend upon characteristics specific to individual presidents rather than organizational or historical conditions alone. Presidents differ in governing style, coalition management, political capital, and tolerance for cabinet turnover. Ignoring these differences could attribute presidential effects to political frameworks or ministerial organizations.
% 
% To account for this possibility, this subsection estimates shared frailty survival models treating presidents as unobserved sources of heterogeneity. These models evaluate whether the principal empirical patterns remain after accounting for president-specific variation in ministerial turnover.
% 
